  "diary": "Woke up to news of the transit strike and honestly felt a little relieved—gave me an excuse to dust off my bike. The ride to South Lake Union was peaceful, cutting through Queen Anne's quiet streets before the city woke up. Work was steady: helped a woman find obscure poetry collections, processed a stack of donated graphic novels, and got the zine workshop materials arranged just right. Grabbed lunch solo at Solstice, some good sourdough and tea, and just sat with my thoughts for a bit. The afternoon flew by with reference questions and last-minute prep. Biked home instead of switching back to the Link once it came online—felt too good to stop. Spent the evening at Magnolia Bluff, watching the light soften over the water, then got lost in mushroom foraging guides. There's something about a day that forces you to slow down that sticks with you.",
  "thought_process": "The strike initially felt like a disruption, but I leaned into it. Biking felt more intentional than defaulting to transit, and I needed that today—something grounding. Work kept me focused, the zine workshop energized me, and staying local during the strike meant I actually sat still at lunch instead of rushing. When the buses came back online, I surprised myself by sticking with the bike. The evening walk was the real shift: the mild weather and that lookout view reminded me why I love this neighborhood. Mushroom foraging has been pulling at my mind lately, and tonight I let myself plan that weekend trip without guilt. The day had a rhythm I didn't force.",
